[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction: Sicilian Sacrifices"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Black is willing to give White a development advantage in order to obtain a central pawn majority after white plays d4 and Black exchanges on d4. If Black is not careful, White's development advantage can allow White to obtain a powerful attack. }
2. Nf3
{ In the Sicilian Defense, White often has a development advantage because 1...c5 is not a developing more, nor does it prepare development. This gives White excellent attacking chances, so one of the most common ways of breaking through with the attack is sacrificing a piece to open the position or break Black's defenses. There are 3 thematic squares for Sicilian piece sacrifices: d5, e6, and f5. If Black has castled kingside and White has castled queenside, White also often sacrifices his g and/or h-pawn in order to open files on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Piece sacrifices on d5"]
[Black "Judit Polgar vs. NN"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "r1bqk2r/3pbppp/p3pn2/1p6/3Q1B2/1BN5/PPP2PPP/R3R1K1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

{ The Nd5 sacrifice is often good when White has a rook on the e-file and Black has not castled yet. This takes advantage of Black's exposed king  (exchanging on d5 opens the e-file)  , and White can use the lead in development to attack Black's king or win material. }
1. Nd5 O-O
{ Black must decline the sacrifice to avoid immidiate loss.   12...exd5  13.Bd6  White wins Black's e7-bishop with a decisive attack.  13...Ne4   13...O-O  14.Bxe7  14...Qc7  15.Bxf8  14.Bxe7  Qxe7  15.Bxd5   12...Nxd5  13.Bxd5  exd5  14.Bd6  If Black was castled, Bd6 would not win material. The Nd5 sacrifice is most often played when Black has not yet castled. }
2. Nxe7+ Qxe7 3. Bd6 { White wins the exchange. } 3... Qd8 4. Bxf8 Qxf8 5. a4
Bb7 6. axb5 axb5 7. c4
{ White's position is much better. In order to secure 1st place in the New York Open, Judit agreed to a draw. }
