[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Piece sacrifices on d5"]
[Black "John Nunn vs. Mihail Marin"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6 7. Qd2 b5 8. f3
Nbd7 9. g4 h6 10. O-O-O Bb7 11. Bd3
{ White can now meet ...b4 with Nce2 without blocking white's light squared bishops's connection with the c4 square. This also develops a piece and prepares Rhe1.   11.h4 !  b4  12.Na4  Qa5  13.b3  Nc5  14.a3  Nxa4  15.axb4  Qc7  16.bxa4  is the modern main line, and is likely more accurate than 11. Bd3. }
11... Ne5 12. Rhe1
{ The conditions are almost ready for the Nd5 sacrifice: White has a rook on the e-file, Black has not castled. The only thing preventing it for now is Black's e5-knight  (which is blocking the e-file)  . }
12... Nfd7
{ 12...b4 !  Black forces White to commit his c3-knight when Nd5 is not ideal.  13.Na4   13.Nd5  exd5  is safe for Black, at very least he can play ...Be7 and O-O. If Black's e5-knight were on c6, White would have a powerful attack.  13...d5  14.exd5  Nxd5  15.f4  This position is slightly better for White, though with best play, Black is able to equalize. }
13. f4 b4
{ 13...Nxg4  14.e5  Another thematic sacrifice ! White sacrifices the g4-pawn to open the g-file  (it is not safe for Black to castle)  and now sacrificed the e5-pawn to open the center. White is attacking with all of his pieces and Black is relatively undeveloped. }
14. Nd5
{ The conditions are met: White has excellent development, Black is uncastled. The obstacle on the e-file  (the e5-knight)  is under attack and will be removed soon. }
14... Nxd3+
{ 14...exd5  15.fxe5  dxe5  16.exd5  White has a huge lead in development and the position is opening up. }
15. Qxd3 exd5 16. exd5
{ As compensation for the knight, white has the open e-file  (Black has not castled yet)  , a space advantage, and a large lead in development. White can increase his initiative with Nc6 or Nf5  (these ideas are thematic after the Nd5 sacrifice)  . }
16... Be7 17. Nc6 { White continues to open the position. } 17... Bxc6 18. dxc6
Nf6 { Other knight moves allow White the same idea. } 19. Bb6 Qxb6 20. Rxe7+
{ Another sacrifice to break through ! White removes the only real defender of Black's king. }
20... Kf8 { 20...Kxe7  21.Qxd6+  Ke8  22.Re1+  with forced checkmate. } 21.
Qxd6
{ White has 2 pawns and a powerful attack for the sacrificed piece. Due to one of White's extra pawns being passed and Black's exposed king, White has a decisive advantage. }
21... Kg8 22. g5 hxg5 23. fxg5 Rc8 24. c7 Qxd6 25. Rxd6 Ng4 26. Rd8+ Kh7 27.
Red7 { Black resigned due to the unstoppable threat of Rxh8 followed by Rd8. }
