1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4 e6 7. Be3 Be7 8.
Qe2 O-O 9. Bb3 Qc7 10. O-O-O a6 11. Rhg1 b5 12. g4 b4 13. Nxc6
{ Because Black has castled, opening the e-file with Nd5 isn't worth a piece. However, if white takes on c6 first then Nd5 can work due to the undefended rook on a8  (White can make a skewer)  . }
13... Qxc6 14. Nd5 exd5
{ 14...Nxd5  15.exd5  Qb7  16.f4  White has the initiative because Black is behind in development. }
15. g5 { Removing the defender of the d5-square. } 15... dxe4
{ 15...Nxe4  16.Bxd5  16...Qa4  17.Bxe4 !  White has excellent centralizaiton and can quickly attack on the kingside. Note how White quickly won back his sacrificed piece while maintaining some positional advantage.   17.Bxa8  White won the exchange, but Black can get an attack.  17...Nc3 !  18.bxc3  Be6  Black's initiative is sufficient for a draw.   15...Nd7  16.Bxd5 }
16. gxf6 Bxf6 17. Bd5 Qa4 18. Qh5
{ White chooses not to grab the a8-rook as to not give Black the initiative. White is only down a pawn, but he has a powerful kingside attack.   18.Bxa8  Qxa2  Black has a dangerous initiative. }
18... Be6
{ Black aims to force trades and counter-attack on the queenside, but it is a bit too late: Black's king is on a half-open g-file and White has a combination to expose it even more. }
19. Rxg7+
{ A second sacrifice follows the first ! The first Nd5 was concrete  (to open the center, some material won back right away)  . The second sacrifice became possible due to the open position  (it was open because of the first sacrifice)  . }
19... Bxg7 { 19...Kxg7  20.Qh6+  Kg8  21.Rg1+  Kh8  22.Qxf6# } 20. Rg1
{ White intends to remove the only piece defending Black's king with a second rook sacrifice: Rxg7+ ! }
20... Rfc8
{ Black begins a queenside counter-attack and gives his king some breathing room.   20...Bxd5  21.Qh6  White will take on g7 with checkmate. }
21. Rxg7+
{ White opens the kingside ! Black's king is left without sufficient defenders, While white can continue the attack with his queen and 2 bishops. }
21... Kxg7 22. Qh6+ Kg8 23. Bxe4
{ White threatens Black's h7-pawn and defends his c2-pawn. } 23... b3
{ Black tries to open the queenside, but it is too late. } 24. Bxh7+ Kh8 25.
Bf5+ Kg8 26. Qh7+ Kf8 27. Bh6+ Ke8 28. Qg8+
{ If White didn't find the accurate winning moves  (there are multiple paths to a win)  , he had at least a perpetual after 24. Bxh7+. }
28... Ke7 29. Bg5+ Kd7 30. Qxf7+ Kc6 31. Bxe6
{ White has won most of his material back and has a decisive attack. } 31...
Kb6 32. Be3+ Ka5 33. Bxc8 Rxc8 34. Qf5+ Rc5 { 34...Kb4  35.a3+  Kc4  36.Qd3# }
35. Bxc5 Qb5 { 35...bxa2  36.b4+  Kb5  37.Qd7+ } 36. Bb4+ Kxb4 37. a3+ Kc4 38.
Qxb5+ axb5 39. cxb3+ Kd3 40. Kd1 *

