1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6 3. Nf3 b5 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bb7 6. Bd3 e6 7. O-O Qc7 8. Qe2
{ If Black hasn't castled, White often plays Qe2 or Re1 in order to have an x-ray on the e-file. This allows some tactical possibilities like the Nd5 sacrifice. }
8... Nc6
{ 8...Nf6  9.e5  Nd5  10.Nxd5  Bxd5  11.a4  White has the initiative and Black is still undeveloped. }
9. Nxc6 Qxc6 10. a4
{ White provokes ...b4 before playing Nd5 in order to force a weakness. ...bxa4 isn't ideal  (Black's a-pawn will be isolated)  and White is threatening Black's b5-pawn. }
10... b4 11. Nd5
{ This is not a sacrifice here because if Black takes on d5 he will lose his Queen. However, Nd5 is very well placed and White can use this to obtain a powerful initiative. }
11... Nf6 { 11...exd5  12.exd5+ } 12. Bc4 { White maintains his d5-knight. }
12... Bd6 13. Rd1
{ White is developing and improving his position before going for an attack. }
13... Bc5
{ ...Bc5 wastes a tempo, but Black realized Bd6 can be vulnerable on the d-file.   13...O-O  14.Nxf6+  gxf6  15.Bh6  White is winning. }
14. Bh6
{ White attempts to remove the defender of the f6-knight. Ever since White played Nd5, he has played energetically  (developing or forcing moves)  to fight for the initiative. }
14... O-O-O { 14...gxh6  15.Nxf6+   14...exd5  15.exd5+ } 15. Bb5
{ These tactics work in White's favor due to his active pieces and Black's exposed king. }
15... axb5 { 15...Qd6  16.Nxf6 } 16. axb5 Qd6 17. Nxf6 Qf8 18. Bxg7
{ Deflecting the queen from defending Bc5. } 18... Qxg7 19. Qc4 d6
{ 19...Qf8  20.e5  White intends on playing Rd6. with the idea of playing Rd6. If black plays Kb8 to get out of the pin, white can take on d7. }
20. Rxd6
{ White removes the defender of the c5-bishop. Black's king is exposed and White's pieces are coordinated. }
20... Qg5 { 20...Rxd6  21.Qxc5+  Kb8  22.Qxd6+ } 21. Nd5
{ Cutting Black's queen off from Bc5. White sacrifices with Nd5 for the second time in this game. White has a desicive initiaitive. }
21... exd5 22. Qxc5+ Kb8 23. Rc6 *

