1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nc6 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. Bc4 Qb6 7. Nb3 e6 8.
Be3 Qc7 9. f4 a6 10. Bd3 b5 11. a3 Be7 12. Qf3 Bb7 13. O-O Rc8
{ 13...O-O  14.Qh3 } 14. Rae1
{ White has finished his development and is ready to attack. } 14... O-O 15.
Qh3 { White intends on playing g4-g5 to attack on the kingside. } 15... b4
{ Black fights for counterplay. } 16. Nd5
{ White fights for the initiative with Nd5 even though Black has already castled.   16.Na4  bxa3  17.bxa3  with ideas of g4-g5, white has the initiative. }
16... exd5 17. exd5
{ White has opened the b1-h7 diagonal for his light-squared bishop. } 17... Nb8
{ 17...Nd8  Be7 is more cramped and can't escape to d8. } 18. Bd4
{ As compensation for the sacrificed piece, White opened the e-file and diagonals for his bishops, which are now aimed at Black's kingside. White's threat is Bxf6 followed by Qxh7#. }
18... g6
{ 18...h6  19.Bxf6  Bxf6  20.Qf5  20...g6  21.Qxf6  White won his piece back and still has a powerful initiative. }
19. Rf3
{ 19. Rf3 is not the best move, but is still dangerous. Even though objectively Black should be fine after 19. Rf3  , it is still easier to play White because he has the initiative.   19.f5 !  White opens the position. This favors him because his pieces are more active.  19...Bxd5  20.Qh4  White has full compensation for the sacrificed piece due to all of his pieces being active and Black's exposed king. White is applying a lot of pressure on Black's f6-knight. }
19... Bxd5 { 19...Nxd5  20.Qxh7+  Kxh7  21.Rh3+  Kg8  22.Rh8# } 20. Rfe3
{ While Black is objectively fine, he has to find tough defensive moves and all of White's pieces are active. }
20... Bd8 21. Qh4 Nbd7 22. Qh6
{ It might look like White lost a tempo with Qh4-h6, but ...Nbd7 could be helping White because Qc7 is cut off from the kingside. }
22... Qb7 23. Rg3 Nc5
{ Too slow. Now White's initiative becomes desicive.   23...Bb6 !  Black needs to trade pieces to reduce the effectiveness of White's attack. }
24. Nxc5 dxc5 25. f5
{ White has a desicive attack. All of his pieces are participating and he is opening the kingside. }
25... cxd4 26. fxg6 fxg6 27. Bxg6 Kh8 28. Qxf8+ Ng8 29. Bf5 Rb8 30. Re8 Qf7 31.
Rh3 *

