1. e4 c5 2. d4 cxd4 3. c3
{ White sacrifices a pawn in exchange for a lead in development and more open files than he would normally get in the Open Sicilian. }
3... dxc3
{ It is safer to decline the gambit with   3...Nf6  4.e5  Nd5  5.cxd4  with a transposition into the 2. c3 Sicilian. White has more space and a stronger center, but Black is better developed and can target White's center with ...d6. }
4. Nxc3 e6 5. Nf3 a6 6. Bc4 { White has a massive lead in development. } 6...
b5 7. Bb3 Bb7 8. O-O
{ White has finished most of his development and is ready to attack. } 8... Ne7
9. Bg5 { White provokes a weakness. } 9... f6
{ 9...h6  10.Bh4  g5  11.Bg3  White has weakened Black's kingside and can open the h-file with h4. }
10. Be3 Ng6 { Black is uncastled and White is well developed. } 11. a4 b4 12.
Nd5
{ To exploit White's lead in development, he should open the position, even at the cost of material. }
12... exd5 13. exd5
{ In exchange for the sacrificed knight, white has received a pawn  (this cramps Black's queenside development)  and has opened the e-file  (White can use this to attack Black's king)  . White has a huge lead in development and is able to bring all of his pieces into the attack. Black has no good way of finishing his development and his king is unsafe in the center and on the kingside. For these reasons, White has more than enough compensation for the sacrificed piece. }
13... Bd6
{ 13...d6  Black prepares ...Nd7, but weakens the e6-square.  14.Nd4  a5  15.Ne6  White has more than enough compensation for the piece. He has the initiative and is very active while black is inactive and mostly far behind in develpment.   13...Be7  14.d6  14...Bf8  15.Re1 }
14. Nd4
{ White's knight heads for the outpost f5-square. White doesn't need to force matters yet as Black still has no good way of finishing his development, so White simply improves his pieces. }
14... Ne7
{ 14...O-O  15.Nf5  15...Be5  16.Qd2  16...d6  17.f4 !  Now that White has finished his development, he begins to force matters.  17...Nxf4  18.Rxf4  More energetic play.  18...Bxf4  19.Bxf4  White has excellent compensation for the sacrificed exchange and has much better piece activity. }
15. Re1
{ White is able to improve his pieces faster than Black is able to bring pieces to the defense due to the cramping effect of White's d5-pawn. White is down a knight, but it is like Black is down all of his queenside pieces, as he can't activate them ! }
15... Kf8 { 15...O-O  16.Nc6 ! } 16. Qd2
{ White keeps improving his position. After he finishes his development, he will be ready to begin forcing play. }
16... Qa5 17. Bf4
{ White aims to trade Black's most active piece  (removing a defender of the e7-knight)  . }
17... Qc7 18. Rxe7
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@'Tactics flow from a superior position' - GM Bobby Fischer@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
18... Bxf4 { 18...Kxe7  19.Nf5+ } 19. Qe2 { White has a decisive attack. }
19... Bxh2+ 20. Kh1 Bd6 21. Ne6+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Piece sacrifices on d5"]
[Black "Emanuel Berg vs. Michal Luch"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rn1qkb1r/1b1p2pp/p3ppn1/8/Pp2P3/1BN1BN2/1P3PPP/R2Q1RK1 w kq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. Nd5
{ To exploit White's lead in development, he should open the position, even at the cost of material. }
1... exd5 2. exd5
{ In exchange for the sacrificed knight, White has received a pawn  (this cramps Black's queenside development)  and has opened the e-file  (White can use this to attack Black's king)  . White has a huge lead in development and is able to bring all of his pieces into the attack. Black has no good way of finishing his development and his king is unsafe in the center and on the kingside. For these reasons, White has more than enough compensation for the sacrificed piece. In the game White rapidly finished his development and played Nd4  (intending Nf5)  and the attack soon broke through. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Piece sacrifices on d5"]
[Black "Judit Polgar vs. Viswanathan Anand"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6 7. f3 b5 8. g4
Nfd7 9. Qd2 Nb6 10. O-O-O N8d7 11. Bd3
{ 11.Ndxb5  axb5  12.Nxb5  Ba6  13.Nxd6+  Bxd6  14.Qxd6  This is the main line. White has sacrificed a piece for 3 pawns and has a powerful initiative in exchange for the sacrificed knight. }
11... Bb7 12. Kb1 Rc8 13. Bg5
{ White is playing very actively. While Black is objectively okay here, White's position is easier to play because White has excellent development and Black is far from castling. }
13... Qc7 14. Rhe1 Ne5 15. f4 Nec4
{ 15...Nxg4  Black wins a pawn, but this hardly matters because White is able to open the position with Black's king still in the center.  16.Qe2  Nf6  17.e5 !  White opens the position. Black's king is unsafe and White is attackin with all of his pieces. Here is a sample line to prove that White's initiative is decisive:  17...dxe5  18.Ncxb5  axb5  19.fxe5  Nfd5  20.Bxb5+  Nd7  21.c4  Nb6  22.Nxe6 !  fxe6  23.Qh5+  g6  24.Qh3  Be7  25.Qxe6  Black is unable to defend agianst the onslaught of all of White's pieces attacking in an open position. }
16. Qc1 h6 17. Nd5
{ A powerful in-between move. Black is unable to accept the sacrificed knight  (he loses by force if he does)  so White is able to obtain the initiative. }
17... Qc5
{ 17...exd5  18.exd5+  Kd7  19.Bf5#   17...Nxd5  18.exd5  Bxd5  19.Bh4  White has full compensation for his sacrificed pawn because of the open central files and his excellent development. }
18. Nb3 Qf2
{ A risky decision. Black's queen is far away from Black's other pieces, it risks getting trapped.   18...Qc6  19.Bh4  White has the initiative, though Black is not losing by force. }
19. Rf1
{ White makes a series of in-between moves in order to maintain the initiative. White does not need to move Bg5 yet. }
19... Qg2 20. Nxb6 Nxb6 21. Qe3 Nc4 22. Qa7 Bxe4 23. Qxa6 Rb8 24. Rg1 hxg5
{ Finally Black captures Bg5, but he loses more material than he gained.   24...Qf3  25.Nd4 }
25. Rxg2 Bxg2 26. Bxc4 bxc4 27. Qa4+
{ Black resigned. Material is roughly equal, but Black is undeveloped and White has 3 passed pawns on the queenside. }
*

