[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. g4
{ The Keres attack is an energetic way of playing against the Scheveningen. White wants to play g5  (gaining space on the kingside and chasing back Nf6)  . }
6... h6 7. h4 Be7
{ 7...Nc6  8.Rg1  h5  9.gxh5  Nxh5  10.Bg5  This is also theory. White has the initiative due to his lead in development and can castle queenside if needed. }
8. g5
{ White usually wants to recapture back on g5 with the pawn, so   8.Rg1  is more common. }
8... hxg5 9. Bxg5 Nc6 10. Qd2 a6 11. O-O-O Bd7 12. f4
{ White has a powerful initiative due to his lead in development. While Black's position is objectively fine, White's position is easier to play. }
12... Nxd4 13. Qxd4 Bc6 14. Rg1 Qa5 15. Bh3 Qc5 16. Qd3 b5 17. f5
{ White has been playing with a lot of energy  (developing and forcing moves)  and now threatens to open the position with fxe6. }
17... b4 18. Be3
{ White makes a couple of in-between moves to improve his position with tempo. }
18... Qa5 19. Qc4 Bb7 20. fxe6
{ Sacrificing the c3 knight to open the position. A common theme in many sicilian sacrifices: sacrificing to open the position when you have a lead in development. This theme is especially prominent if Black delays castling for a long time. }
20... bxc3 21. Rxg7 { White has a decisive attack. } 21... d5 22. Qb3
{ 22.exf7+ !  White had a beautiful Queen sacrifice which forces checkmate !  22...Kf8  23.Be6  dxc4   23...Kxg7  24.Rg1+  Kf8   24...Kh7  25.Bf5#  25.Bh6+  Rxh6  26.Rg8+  Nxg8  27.fxg8=Q#  24.Bh6  White is threatening Rg8#.  24...Bc5   24...Rxh6  25.Rg8+  Nxg8  26.fxg8=Q#  25.Rh7+  The only move which wins. White forces checkmate.  25...Ke7  26.f8=Q+  Double check !  26...Kxe6  27.Qf7+  Ke5  28.Qe7+  Bxe7  29.Rxe7# }
22... cxb2+
{ Even though White missed the queen sacrifice, White's attack is still decisive. Black can't defend against the coordinated efforts of all of White's pieces, especially since Black has not castled. }
23. Kb1
{ White hides behind Black's pawn. Since Black can't take his own pawns, the b2-pawn is an excellent shield which prevents Black from obtaining a counter-attack. }
23... Qb5 24. exf7+ Kf8 25. Rdg1
{ White brings all of his pieces to the kingside and quickly wins. } 25... Qxb3
26. Bh6
{ White sacrifices his queen to accelerate his attack.   26.axb3  Ba3  27.e5  This is also winning for White, but 26. Bh6 is more forcing. }
26... Ng4
{ 26...Rxh6  Black unguards the g8-square, allowing White to force checkmate.  27.Rg8+  Kxf7   27...Nxg8  28.fxg8=Q#  28.R1g7#   26...Bc5  27.Rh7+  Ke7  28.f8=Q# }
27. Rh7+ Nxh6 28. Rxh8+ Kxf7 29. Rh7+
{ Black resigns. White can play axb3 next and Black's King is in a mating net. }
