{ White has finished his development and is ready to attack. } 11... Qb6 12.
Nb3
{ 12.Nd5 !  is a more effective way of fighting for the initiative. Here are some ways the game could continue:  12...Qxd4   12...exd5  13.Nc6 !  White's d4-knight was hanging, so it might well gain something in exchange. If Black captures on c6, he will lose a piece due to exd5+ followed by dxc6.  13...dxe4   13...Bxc6  14.exd5+  Be7  15.dxc6  Nc5  16.Bxf6  gxf6  17.Bf5  White has more than full compensation for the sacrificed knight in the form of a pawn, more active pieces, Black's unsafe king and White's superior pawn structure. White is also likely to win another pawn back with Rxd6.  14.Bxe4  This position is very complicated, but White has the initiative  (and probably an objective advantage)  .  13.Bxf6  gxf6   13...Nxf6 ?  14.Bxb5+  14.Bxb5  14...Qc5  15.b4 !   15.Nxf6+  Kd8  16.Nxd7  Qxb5  17.Nxf8  Rxf8  18.Qa3  White has sufficient compensation for the sacrificed piece, but no more.  15...Qxb5  16.Nc7+  Ke7  17.Nxb5  axb5  18.Qd3  Ra6  19.Qxb5  There is an odd material balance on the board  (Queen and 2 pawns against 3 minor pieces)  but White has a material advantage and an active position, so he is objectively better. }
12... b4 13. Na4 Qc7 14. Nd4
{ White still has the initiative, but Black has better defending chances than if White had played 12. Nd5. }
14... Be7 15. Qh3 { White prepares to sacrifice on e6. } 15... Nc5 16. Nxc5
dxc5 17. Nxe6
{ White sacrifices a piece for 2 pawns and the initiative. Black will be unable to castle and White can bring all of his pieces into the attack. }
17... fxe6 18. Bc4
{ White would rather capture on e6 with his bishop.   18.Qxe6 ?!  Qc6  19.Qb3  O-O-O  White has reasonable compensation for the sacrificed piece, but Black has castled safely. }
18... Rd8
{ 18...O-O  19.Qxe6+  Kh8  20.e5  White wins back more material than he is lost while keeping his initiative. }
19. Qxe6 Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 { White threatens to play Qf7#. } 20... Rf8 21. Bxf6
{ White chooses to win some material back or force a weakening of Black's light-squares. }
21... Rxf6
{ 21...gxf6 ?  22.Qf5  White has a decisive attack because Black is unable to meet Qh5+ with ...g6. }
22. Qg8+ Bf8 23. g3
{ White's compensation is long-term: Black is unable to use his extra piece effectively. After White wins the h7-pawn, White will have 3 strong  (possibly passed)  pawns for the piece. Black has to find many tough defensive moves to even have chances of equalizing }
23... Bc8
{ Too slow. To have chances of equalizing, Black needed to trade light-squared bishops.   23...Bc6 !  24.Qxh7  Bb5 !  Black aims to trade light-squared bishops, as White's light-squared bishop was controling many important squares. While White is pressing here, Black has much better chances to hold than in the game. }
24. e5 Rb6 25. Qxh7
{ White's pawn chain coordinates nicely with White's light-squared bishop as they control opposite colored squares. }
25... Be6 26. Qg6+ Qf7 27. Qe4 Qc7
{ 27...Bxc4  28.Qa8+  Ke7  29.Qd8+  Ke6  30.Qc8+  Ke7  31.Qd7# } 28. h4
{ Now Black trading light-squared bishops is not favorable as White has made too much progress advancing his pawns. Black is lost. }
28... Bxc4 29. Qxc4 Qc6 30. b3 g6 31. Qe2
{ White wants to trade his h-pawn for Black's g-pawn so that he would have 3 connected passed pawns. }
31... Qe6 32. h5 Rb7 33. Qe4 Rg7 34. hxg6 Qxg6 35. f5 *

