1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Be2
{ While 3. Be2 is playable, 3. d4 is more energetic. } 3... e6 4. O-O d6 5. d4
cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nf6 7. Bf3
{ White doesn't want to block his c-pawn  (he wants to play c4 before Nc3)  , but objectively, Bf3 harms White's piece coordination more than it gains.   7.Nc3  is stronger. }
7... Ne5 8. c4 { This is a hedgehog pawn structure where Bf3 is inactive. }
8... Nxf3+
{ Black gains the bishop pair but improves the position of White's queen. Since Ne5 was more active than Bf3, this exchange was premature. }
9. Qxf3 Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. b3 Nd7 12. Bb2 Bf6 13. Rad1
{ White now has excellent piece activity and is ready to play for a kingside attack. }
13... a6 14. Qg3 Qc7 15. Kh1
{ Prophylaxis, White is preparing for f4  (he doesn't want ...Qb6 to pin Nd4)  . }
15... Rd8 16. f4 b6 17. f5 { White wants to open the f-file with fxe6. } 17...
Be5
{ 17...e5  critically weakens the d5-square.  18.Nd5  White's pieces are dominating and White's attack continues. }
18. fxe6
{ Black's queenside is undeveloped, White is attacking with all of his pieces, the only thing left to obtain a decisive attack is to open the position. This is worth White's queen, especially since White is soon able to play Nd5. }
18... Bxg3 19. exf7+ Kh8 20. Nd5
{ @@StartBlockQuote@@'The point of Alekhine's combination. The combined force of the remaining pieces dominates the board, despite Black's huge material advantage. Saemisch was so terrified by the opponent's multiple threats that, to the surprise of the audience, he simply resigned ! In fact, all variations prove that his decision, although a bit premature, was fully justified !' - GM Garry Kasparov@@EndBlockQuote@@ }
