1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Bc4 Be7 8.
Qe2 a6 9. O-O-O Qc7 10. Bb3 Na5
{ Black is playing a risky setup: he is behind on development and is delaying castling. }
11. g4 { White begins a pawn storm to fight for the initiative. } 11... b5 12.
g5 Nxb3+
{ Black must capture White's light-squared bishop before White sacrifices it on e6.   12...Nd7 ?  13.Bxe6 !  This typical sacrifice gives White a winning initiative.  13...fxe6  14.Nxe6 }
13. axb3 Nd7 14. Nf5
{ A typical sacrifice ! White sacrifices his knight on f5 in order to obtain the d5-square  (a typical outpost for Nc3)  , the e-file  (White can use this to attack if Black doesn't castle)  , and a kingside space advantage  (White can use this to pawn storm if Black castles)  . }
14... exf5
{ Black has to accept the sacrificed piece, or White will obtain the initiative for free. }
15. Nd5 Qd8 16. exf5 { White has full compensation for the piece. } 16... O-O
{ Since the center is open, Black wanted his king to escape to the kingside, but due to White's huge space advantage  (and pawn lever f6)  , Black's king would have been safer in the center.   16...Bb7  is Black's best defencive try.  17.f6  gxf6  18.Rhe1  White has full compensation for the sacrificed piece, but Black isn't losing by force yet. }
17. f6 { White forced the opening of the kingside. } 17... gxf6 18. Bd4
{ White threatens to capture Black's e7-bishop. } 18... Ne5
{ 18...Re8  19.gxf6 } 19. gxf6 { White opens the g-file. } 19... Bxf6 20. Rhg1+
{ White's attack is decisive. White is attacking with all of his pieces, Black's kingside is open, and Black hasn't even finished his development yet. }
20... Bg7 { 20...Kh8  21.Bb6 } 21. Bxe5 dxe5 22. Qxe5 f6 23. Ne7+ Kf7
{ 23...Kh8  24.Rxd8  fxe5  25.Rxf8+  Bxf8  26.Rg8# } 24. Qh5+ *

