[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Piece sacrifices on f5"]
[Black "Tabban vs. Boursies"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bg5 e6 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3
Qc7 9. O-O-O Nbd7 10. g4
{ White is playing a very aggressive setup against the Najdorf. White's plan is to finish his development and pawn storm on the kingside. }
10... b5 11. Bxf6
{ White gives up the bishop pair in order to gain a tempo with g5. } 11... Nxf6
12. g5 Nd7 13. a3
{ White prevents ...b4 for the time being. If Black wants to play ...b4 he will have to prepare it  (for example ...Rb8)  and then ...b4 will have the consiquence of isolating his a6-pawn and not forcing White's c3-knight to move.   13.f5  This pawn sacrifice is also playable. Mainline theory goes  13...Bxg5+  14.Kb1  Ne5  15.Qh5  Qd8  and here White has a pleasant choice of how he will fight for the initiative.  16.Rg1   16.h4   16.Nxe6 !? }
13... Rb8 { Black prepares ...b4. } 14. h4
{ White prepares f5  (he doesn't want to sacrifice the g5-pawn because he can later open the kingside with g6)  . }
14... b4 15. axb4 Rxb4 16. Bh3
{ White has finished his development and is now threatening the thematic Bxe6 sacrifice. }
16... Nc5 { Black prevents Bxe6. } 17. Rhf1
{ White has finished his development and is now preparing to open the position with f5. }
17... Qb7 18. f5 O-O 19. f6 Bd8 20. fxg7 Kxg7 21. Qh5
{ White has a powerful attack because Black's kingside is open and White has excellent development. Due to Black's counterplay on the b-file, Black isn't losing, but he has to find several tough moves in order to defend. }
21... Kg8 22. Qh6
{ Since White's attack is so fast, Black needs to fight for active counterplay. }
22... Rc4
{ Too slow. 22... Rc4 is the losing move. If white had his c3 knight on f6, he would checkmate Black shortly.   22...Rxb2 !  Black opens the queenside !  23.Rf3  White prepares Rdg1 with g6. Black needs to play extremely accurately in order to bail out with a draw.   23.g6  is similar and is likely to transpose  23...Na4  Otherwise Black is losing. White's attack is very powerful, but if Black finds several computer moves he will be able to give a perpetual check and escape with a draw.  24.g6  hxg6  25.Bxe6 !  Bxe6  26.Rg1  This is a very complicated position, anything could happen in a real game, but the objective evaluation of the position is likely dynamically balanced.  26...Rb1+   26...Rxc2+  is another crazy line that ends in dynamic equality  27.Nxc2  Bf6  28.Nxa4  Bg7  29.Qd2  Rb8  30.Qxd6  Bf8  White's king is exposed enough for Black to be able to force a draw  (otherwise White is up a rook)  .  31.Qd4   31.Rxg6+ !?  Kh7   31...fxg6 ?  32.Qxe6+  32.Rxe6  Bxd6  33.Rxd6  Qxe4  34.Rxf7+  Kg8  35.Rdd7  Qxh4  36.Rg7+  Kh8  37.Rh7+  Qxh7  38.Rxh7+  Kxh7  with an equal endgame.  31...Bg7  32.Qd6  with a perpetual. Conclusion: When White is fighting for the initiative in these types of positions, Black's position is often very tough to play.  27.Kd2  Rxg1  28.Nxe6  Bg5+  29.hxg5  Rg2+  30.Ke1  Rg1+  31.Kd2 }
23. Bf5
{ The winning move, as white can maneuver his c3-knight to f6 via d5.   23.Nf5 ?!  would be enough for a draw, but the c3 knight is nessisary to block Rc4.  23...exf5  24.exf5  White has an initiative sufficient for a draw, as Black can sacrifice the exchange on c3.   24.Nd5 ?  Qb3  wins for Black. White is 1 tempo short. If Bh3 was missing but Nd4 was still present, this option would not be available for Black. }
23... exf5 24. exf5
{ This complicates the win and allows Black defending chances, though white still has the initiative.   24.Nd5 !  easily wins  24...f6  White was threatening Nf6+   24...Ne6  25.Nxf5  25.gxf6  with Rg1+ }
24... f6 25. gxf6 Rxf6 { 25...Bxf6  26.Rg1+ } 26. Rg1+ Kh8 27. Rde1 Be6
{ 27...Ne6 !  Allowing the defensive resource Nf8 in some lines.  28.Qe3  Nf8  29.Ne4  White is the one playing for a win, but he is not clearly winning here, like he would have been after 24. Nd5 ! }
28. Qe3 Rxd4 29. Qxd4 Bf7 30. Nd5 { White has a decisive initiative. } 30...
Qc6 31. Kb1 Qa4 32. Nxf6
{ Black resigns. If 32... Qxd4 white wins with 33. Rd8+ Bxd8 34. Rg8#. Conclusion: The Nf5  (or Bf5)  sacrifice is a very powerful attacking motif in the Sicilian so that White can gain the d5-square and accelerate White's kingside pawn storm. }
