[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Bg5 e6 7. Qd2 a6 8.
O-O-O { White has finished his development and is ready to attack. } 8... Bd7
9. f3 { White strengthens his center and prepares to play g4. } 9... b5 10. Kb1
Be7 11. Be3 { White prepares g4-g5. } 11... Rb8 12. g4 h6 13. Nxc6
{ White opens the d-file and clears the d4-square for Nc3. } 13... Bxc6 14. Ne2
{ White's knight was not very well placed on c3  (d5 was well controlled and there were no good sacrifices on f5)  so White maneuvers it to d4. }
14... Nd7 15. Nd4 Ba8 16. h4 { White continues his kingside pawn storm. } 16...
Ne5
{ 16...Bxh4 ?  17.g5 !  White wins due to the x-ray on Rh8. For example:  17...Bxg5  18.Bxg5  Qxg5  19.Qxg5  hxg5  20.Rxh8+  White has a decisive material advantage. }
17. b3
{ White prevents ...Nc4. Notice how White prevents the opponent's dangerous ideas before continuing the attack. This position doesn't need to be a race because White has more resources available - he is better developed - so why allow counterplay ? }
17... O-O 18. Rg1
{ White prepares to play f4 by protecting his g4-pawn. White is okay with Black taking his h4-pawn because doing so would open the h-file, accelerating White's attack. }
18... Bxh4 19. g5 { White continues to open the kingside. } 19... hxg5 20. Bxg5
Bxg5 21. Rxg5 Qf6 22. Bh3
{ White prepares Rdg1 and eyes potential sacrifices on e6 or f5  (another method of opening Black's kingside)  . }
22... Rfe8 23. Rdg1 Ng6
{ Black needs to be accurate to defend against White's attack, and passively defending will not do the job.   23...g6  is a better defencive try, but after  24.f4  Nc4  This piece sacrifice is essentially forced, Black will have insufficient compensation for White's initiative otherwise.   24...Nd7  25.f5  White has a desicive attack.  25.bxc4  bxc4+  26.Kc1  Bxe4  27.Qe3  d5   27...Bd5  28.Bg2  28.Bg2  Black has 3 pawns for the piece. This is insufficient compensation because after White trades bishops, his attack will continue and Black's extra pawns are well blockaded. }
24. Bf5 { White opens the g-file. } 24... exf5 { Otherwise Black allows Bxg6. }
25. exf5 Ne7
{ 25...Ne5  26.f4  Nd7  27.Qc3 !  White can take twice on g7 and play Ne6 double check and soon checkmate. }
26. Rxg7+
{ White has destroyed the defenses around Black's king. Other than this, White has also recieved 2 pawns for his sacrificed bishop. }
26... Kf8
{ 26...Qxg7  27.Rxg7+  Kxg7  28.Qg5+  Kf8  29.Qh6+  Kg8  30.f6  Qg7# is unstoppable. }
27. Qh2 { White brings his queen into the attack. } 27... Nd5 28. Rxf7+
{ White prevents Black's king from escaping to d7. White's 3 remaining pieces are still enough to give White a decivise attack. }
28... Qxf7 { 28...Kxf7  29.Qh7+  Kf8  30.Rg8# } 29. Qxd6+ Re7
{ 29...Qe7  30.Qh6+  Kf7  31.Qg6+  Kf8  32.Qg8# } 30. Qxb8+ Qe8 31. Qd6
{ White has won back all of his sacrificed material while retaining his massive initiative. Black resigned. }
