[White "Piece sacrifices on f5"]
[Black "Bela Perenyi vs. Attila Schneider"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Be3 e6 7. g4
{ White fights for the initiative in a very aggressive way. His intention is to gain space with g5, driving back Black's kingside knight. }
7... e5 { Black aims to exploit 7. g4, White's g4-pawn is now hanging. } 8. Nf5
g6 9. g5
{ White sacrifices his knight for a kingside space advantage and the d5-square. If White wins Black's f6-knight, Black will have no development while White can develop his pieces rapidly.   9.Bg2  gxf5  10.exf5  is also playable. White has full compensation for the piece in view of his kingside space advantage, d5-square, and easier development. Black has an extra piece, but his pieces are passive in comparison to White's pieces. In this variation compared to 9. g5, White's compensation for the piece is more positional than dynamic. }
9... gxf5 10. exf5
{ 10.exf6  f4!  gives Black the initiative. White can force a draw with  11.Bc4  exf3  12.Bxf7+  Kxf7  13.Qh5+  , but White shouldn't be thinking of a draw so early in the game. }
10... d5
{ Black refuses to only play defense  (which would likely have resulted in a quick loss)  and fights for central counterplay.   10...Nfd7  11.Qh5  White's attack should be decisive.   10...Ng8 ?!  11.Nd5  11...Nd7  12.Qf3 }
11. Qf3
{ 11.gxf6  d4  12.Bc4  is another way of fighting for the initiative. White has full compensation for the sacrificed piece. }
11... Ne4
{ Black gives back one pawn to slow White's initiative.   11...d4  12.O-O-O  White has excellent compensation for the sacrificed material because White is attacking with all of his pieces and Black has almost no development. }
12. Nxe4 dxe4 13. Qxe4
{ White has 2 pawns and a powerful initiative for the sacrificed piece. } 13...
Nc6 14. Bc4 Bd7
{ Too slow. Black allows White to castle queenside and ...Bd7 was not very useful from Black's point of view.   14...Qd7 !  is a better defense, though White still has a powerful initiative after  15.g6 !   15.Bd3  is less forcing, with positional compensation for the sacrificed piece.   14...Qa5+ ?!  15.c3  Bd7  16.O-O-O  O-O-O  17.Bxf7  White has 3 pawns and a powerful initiative for the sacrificed piece. }
15. O-O-O { White's initiative is now decisive. } 15... Qc7 16. Rhe1
{ White could have won by force with   16.Bb6 !!  Qxb6  17.Bxf7+  Kxf7  18.Qd5+  Kg7  19.Qxd7+  Be7  20.f6+ }
16... f6
{ Black wants to triple White's pawns, but White has a powerful combination which exploits his lead in development and Black's exposed king.   16...O-O-O  17.Bxf7  White has 3 powerful pawns for the sacrificed piece. }
17. Rxd7 Qxd7 { 17...Kxd7  18.Be6+  Kd8  19.Rd1+  Bd6  20.gxf6 } 18. gxf6
{ Black is not able to castle queenside due to Be6 and Black's king will lose if it stays in the center  (all of White's pieces are attacking and the center is opening up)  . }
18... Bd6 19. Be6 Qc7 20. f7+ Kd8 21. Rd1 Rc8 22. Qxe5
{ 22...Nxe5  23.Bg5+  Qe7  24.Rxd6+  Kc7  25.Bxd7  Black resigns. This was another example of White sacrificing his knight on f5 in order to obtain the d5-square and a kingside space advantage. Such positions are usually very difficult for Black to defend. }
