[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Piece sacrifices on f5"]
[Black "Bela Perenyi vs. Attila Schneider"]
[Result "*"]
[FEN "rnbqkb1r/1p3p1p/p2p1np1/4pN2/4P1P1/2N1B3/PPP2P1P/R2QKB1R w KQkq - 0 1"]
[SetUp "1"]

1. g5
{ White sacrifices his knight for a kingside space advantage and the d5-square. If White wins Black's f6-knight, Black will have no development while White can develop his pieces rapidly. }
1... gxf5 2. exf5
{ White has full compensation for the sacrificed knight in the form of a pawn, a lead in development, open files  (easier development)  , the d5-square, and a kingside space advantage. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Other sacrifices"]
[Black "Anatoly Karpov vs. Viktor Korchnoi"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 8. Qd2
{ White's plan is to castle queenside, open the h-file  (h4-h5)  , trade dark-squared bishops  (Bh6-xg7)  and attack on the open h-file, exploting the newly weakened dark squares. }
8... O-O 9. Bc4 Bd7 10. h4 Rc8
{ 10...h5  Black prevents h5, but White will often sacrifice 2 pawns with g4 hxg4 h5 to open the kingside. For example:  11.O-O-O  Ne5  12.Bb3  Rc8  13.Kb1  Re8  14.g4 !  hxg4  15.h5 !  Nxh5  16.Bh6  e6  17.Rdg1  White's attack is worth more than Black's 2 extra pawns.  17...Qf6  18.fxg4  Bxh6  19.Qxh6  Qg7  20.Qd2  Nf6  21.g5  Nh5  22.Nce2  White has won one of his pawns back and has a decisive attack. His plan is to trade knights   Ng3  , unclogging the h-file, double rooks on the h-file, play Qf4-f6  (to trade queens and remove the only real defender of Black's king)  followed by Rh8+ and R1h7 checkmate. }
11. Bb3 { White moves his bishop off of Rc8's x-ray. } 11... Ne5 12. O-O-O Nc4
{ 12...h5 !?  Black prevents h5 but allows the double-pawn sacrifice g4 ...hxg4 h5. White usually plays this after some prophylactic moves  (Kb1 and/or Bg5)  . }
13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14. h5
{ Playing h4-h5 without g4 is usually more effective than g4 first because in these types of positions, attacking speed is very important  (a delay can give Black more chances of generating queenside counterplay)  , and it is worth sacrificing a pawn to open the h file. If Black's attack was slowed by a tempo then g4 before h4 gives White a similar attack without losing a pawn. }
14... Nxh5 { Taking with the pawn exposes Black's kingside too much. } 15. g4
Nf6 16. Nde2
{ Prophylaxis ! White wants to bring his queen into the attack without allowing ...Rxc3  (exposing White's queenside)  so White defends against Black's only source of counterplay before continuing his attack. }
16... Qa5 17. Bh6 Bxh6 18. Qxh6 Rfc8 19. Rd3
{ Black has no counterplay due to White's defensive moves Nde2 and Rd3. Now White can finish Black off without having to calculate complex variations Where Black gets counterplay. }
19... R4c5
{ Supposedly defending against White's threat of g5. But this is too slow - White can play it anyways. This is Black's only mistake this game other than not playing the accurate 10... h5 or 12... h5  (these moves have their dangers as well)  but it was enough to lose.   19...Qd8  is stronger, but White still has a huge attack on the h file and can play  20.g5  Nh5  21.Nf4  Black is forced to trade queens to prevent White's attack from becoming decisive.  21...Qf8  22.Qxf8+  Kxf8  23.Nxh5  gxh5  24.Rxh5  White is much better in this endgame due to his superior pawn structure. }
20. g5
{ Sacrificing a pawn to prepare Nd5  (removing the defender of Black's kingside)  without allowing ...Rxd5. }
20... Rxg5 { 20...Nh5  21.Nf4  White has a winning attack. } 21. Rd5 Rxd5 22.
Nxd5 { White prepares to remove the defender of Black's h7-pawn with Nxf6+. }
22... Re8 { 22...Nxd5  loses to  23.Qxh7+  Kf8  24.Qh8# } 23. Nef4
{ White prepares to to take on f6, take on h7 and play Nd5  (before or after Qh8+)  cutting off the Blacks king's escape squares. }
23... Bc6 24. e5
{ An interferance tactic which prevents the Black queen from guarding the 7th rank. }
24... Bxd5 { 24...dxe5  25.Nxf6+  exf6  26.Nh5  White has a winning attack. }
25. exf6 exf6 26. Qxh7+ Kf8 27. Qh8+
{ Black resigns. 27... Ke7 28. Nxd5+ Qxd5 29. Re1+ wins Black's rook or queen. }
